These scripts (along with setting $PULP_TOP_DIR in your environment) can be
used to setup an isolated pulp environment for development.

Steps:
0. Make sure you have python-virtualenv installed.

   ###########################################################################
   sudo yum install python-virtualenv
   ###########################################################################

1. Choose a top level directory where you want to setup your development
   environment, and set $PULP_TOP_DIR to this directory.  We'll use /tmp/pulp.

   ###########################################################################
   export PULP_TOP_DIR=/tmp/pulp
   ###########################################################################

   NOTE: make sure you have $PULP_TOP_DIR defined anytime you use any of the
   commands in the steps below.

2. Run pulp-dev.py as usual, but we need to specify an additional option of -A,
   which tells the script what user we intend to use to start apache.  We'll
   use jslagle, since I'm the one writhing this.

   ###########################################################################
   python pulp-dev.py -I -A jslagle
   ###########################################################################

   What this does differently
   ==========================
   It checks to see if  $PULP_TOP_DIR is defined, and if so, setups all the
   installed and symlinked files based off this root directory, instead of /.

   It also prepares an isolated apache environment for running Pulp.  It copies
   a chunk of /etc/httpd as it already exists on your system into the
   $PULP_TOP_DIR.  

   Since some files need special modifications to run out of $PULP_TOP_DIR, the
   script also makes those changes.  Therefore, you may notice that some files
   are copied from your pulp checkout into $PULP_TOP_DIR instead of symlinked
   as pulp-dev.py noramlly does.  Their copied instead of symlinked to prevent
   accidental checkins into git.  If you're interested what those are, read
   the source of pulp-dev.py.

   One final note, pulp-dev.py also sets up a python virtualenv environment
   based at $PULP_TOP_DIR.  You'll notice we'll be making use of this provided
   interpreter to finish the setup.

3. Install the Pulp source as usual, but use the python interpreter from our
   virtualenv environment.

   ###########################################################################
   cd ~/code/pulp/platform/src
   $PULP_TOP_DIR/bin/python setup.py install

   cd ~/code/rpm-support/src
   $PULP_TOP_DIR/bin/python setup.py install
   ###########################################################################

4. Edit $PULP_TOP_DIR/etc/pulp/admin/admin.conf and change the port to 8443.
   Our apache instance hosts http on 8080 and https on 8443.

5. Edit $PULP_TOP_DIR/etc/pulp/server.conf and optionally change the database
   name.  You do this if you don't want to use the already defined
   pulp_database for this pulp environment.  It's up to you.  If you do change
   the name, you need to run pulp-migrate.

   Note: The databases for Pulp v1 and v2 are not compatible, so this would be
   a good reason to change the name.

   ###########################################################################
   ~/code/pulp/playpen/pulp_top_dir/pulp-migrate
   ###########################################################################

6. Start the apache server:

   ###########################################################################
   ~/code/pulp/playpen/pulp_top_dir/start-server
   ###########################################################################

   There's also a stop-server script:

   ###########################################################################
   ~/code/pulp/playpen/pulp_top_dir/start-server
   ###########################################################################

7. Use this pulp-admin to interact with your Pulp development environment:

   ###########################################################################
   ~/code/pulp/playpen/pulp_top_dir/pulp-admin
   ###########################################################################

   The apache logs are (of course) relative to your $PULP_TOP_DIR at
   $PULP_TOP_DIR/var/log/httpd.

8. Enjoy hacking Pulp :).

